NAME - ::<namespace>:: emulation_bfd_config

DESCRIPTION

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

This command is used to create/modify/delete/enable/disable a BFD router.
Each BFD router can have multiple BFD router interfaces.
Each router interface is associated with a protocol interface.
By specifying the intf_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to intf_count of directly connected interfaces per BFD router.
By specifying the loopback_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to loopback_count of unconnected interfaces per connected interface.
By specifying the gre_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to gre_count of unconnected interfaces per connected interface(if no loopback_... parameters are specified) or per unconnected interface(if loopback_... parameters are specified).
At the end the number of BFD router interfaces per BFD router will be: intf_count * loopback_count * gre_count.
Each BFD router interface will be associated to:

  • a directly connected interface, if the user specifies only the intf_... parameters
  • an unconnected/loopback interface, if the user specifies the intf_... and the loopback_... parameters
  • a GRE tunnel, if the user specifies:
    • the intf_... and the loopback_... and gre_... parameters
    • the intf_ and the gre_... parameters

SYNOPSIS - ::<namespace>::emulation_bfd_config

List arguments in the alphabetical order or in the reverse alphabetical order.

ARGUMENTS

[M] indicates if the argument is mandatory on the supported platform.

-atm_encapsulation

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

This parameter specifies the ATM encapsulation for an ATM router interface. The options are VccMuxIPV4Routed, VccMuxIPV6Routed, VccMuxBridgedEthernetFCS, VccMuxBridgedEthernetNoFCS, LLCRoutedCLIP, LLCBridgedEthernetFCS, LLCBridgedEthernetNoFCS.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is a BFD router interface.

DEFAULT

LLCBridgedEthernetFCS

-control_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Sets the rate control interval at port level. If the control interval is set using multiple calls to emulation_bfd_config, the last value will be the one set.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify.

DEFAULT

 None

-count

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The number of BFD routers that need to be created.This option is valid only when -mode is create.

DEFAULT

1

-echo_rx_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

This is the minimum interval, in microseconds, between received BFD Echo packets that this system is capable of supporting. If this value is zero, the transmitting system does not support the receipt of BFD Echo packets. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

-echo_timeout

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The value must be chosen in such a way so that the session liveliness should be verified by Echo conveniently. Remember, since Echo Time Out is configurable, it is possible that the session may have a higher Echo Time Out than BFD Control Time Out. On expiry of Echo Time Out the session will be deleted and the entire process of BFD session establishment will happen from the DOWN state. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -echo_tx_interval is present and has a value greater than or equal to 50 and -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

1500

-echo_tx_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

If Echo Tx interval is configured, Echo packets will be sent at an interval of Echo Tx interval. If the configurable Echo Tx interval is not set to a value greater than 50, the transmitter will use the Echo Rx interval of the connected device to send its Echo Packets. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

-enable_ctrl_plane_independent

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

If set, the transmitting system's BFD implementation does not share fate with its control plane (in other words, BFD is implemented in the forwarding plane and can continue to function through disruptions in the control plane). If clear, the transmitting system's BFD implementation shares fate with its control plane. The use of this bit is application dependent and is outside the scope of this specification. This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

-enable_demand_mode

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

BFD has two operating modes which may be selected, as well as an additional function that can be used in combination with the two modes, the echo function. This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

Valid options are:

0

Asynchronous mode. In this mode, the systems periodically send BFD Control packets to one another, and if a number of those packets in a row are not received by the other system, the session is declared to be down. If -enable_demand_mode is set to 0, the system will be in asynchronous mode.

1

Demand mode. In this mode, once a BFD session is established, the systems stop sending BFD Control packets, except when either system feels the need to verify connectivity explicitly, in which case a short sequence of BFD Control packets is sent, and then the protocol again stops sending Control packets. If enable_demand_mode is set to 1, the system will be in demand mode.

DEFAULT

0

-flap_tx_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

BFD sessions will flap every flap_tx_interval (ms).This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

-gre_count

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The number of GRE tunnels to be created per directly connected interface or per loopback interface. The presence/absence of loopback_... parameters specifies whether the source of the GRE tunnel is the directly connected interface or the loopback interface. If the loopback_... parameters are present the GRE interface will be connected through the loopback interface, otherwise it will be connected through the directly connected interface.This option is valid only when -mode is create and -gre_ip_addr and/or -gre_ipv6_addr are present.

DEFAULT

0

-gre_ip_addr

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The first GRE tunnel IPv4 address that will be configured.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is a BFD router interface.

DEFAULT

 None

-gre_ip_addr_step

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The IPv4 address incrementing step of the GRE tunnels that will be configured.This option is valid only when -mode is create and -gre_ip_addr is present.

DEFAULT

0.0.1.0

-gre_ip_addr_lstep

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The IPv4 address incrementing step of the GRE tunnels that will be configured when passing from one loopback interface to another.
This option is valid only when -mode is create and -gre_ip_addr is present.
When gre_src_ip_addr_mode is routed, then both gre_ip_addr_cstep and gre_ip_addr_lstep must be present if this kind of incrementing is wanted. If only one of them is present, the two parameters are ignored and only gre_ip_addr_step is taken into account.
When gre_src_ip_addr_mode is connected, then only gre_ip_addr_cstep will be considered. If gre_ip_addr_cstep is not present, the incrementing is based on gre_ip_addr_step.
Example:

  1. The GRE tunnels have the loopback interfaces as source.
    intf_count 2
    loopback_count 2
    gre_count 3
    gre_src_ip_addr_mode routed
    gre_ip_addr 1.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_step 0.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_lstep 0.0.1.0
    gre_ip_addr_cstep 0.1.0.0
    The following list of GRE IP addresses will be generated:
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE1 - 1.0.0.1;
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE2 - 1.0.0.2;
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE3 - 1.0.0.3;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE4 - 1.0.1.1;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE5 - 1.0.1.2;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE6 - 1.0.1.3;

    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE7 - 1.1.0.1;
    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE8 - 1.1.0.2;
    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE9 - 1.1.0.3;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE10 - 1.1.1.1;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE11 - 1.1.1.2;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE12 - 1.1.1.3;
  2. The GRE tunnels have the connected interfaces as source
    intf_count 2
    gre_count 3
    gre_src_ip_addr_mode connected
    gre_ip_addr 1.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_step 0.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_cstep 0.1.0.0
    The following list of GRE IP addresses will be generated:
    Connected1, GRE1 - 1.0.0.1;
    Connected1, GRE2 - 1.0.0.2;
    Connected1, GRE3 - 1.0.0.3;

    Connected2, GRE7 - 1.1.0.1;
    Connected2, GRE8 - 1.1.0.2;
    Connected2, GRE9 - 1.1.0.3;

DEFAULT

 None

DESCRIPTION

If gre_ip_addr_cstep is not present, the incrementing is based on gre_ip_addr_step.See example under gre_ip_addr_lstep.

NAME - <namespace>::emulation_bfd_config

DESCRIPTION

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

This command is used to create/modify/delete/enable/disable a BFD router.
Each BFD router can have multiple BFD router interfaces.
Each router interface is associated with a protocol interface.
By specifying the intf_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to intf_count of directly connected interfaces per BFD router.
By specifying the loopback_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to loopback_count of unconnected interfaces per connected interface.
By specifying the gre_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to gre_count of unconnected interfaces per connected interface(if no loopback_... parameters are specified) or per unconnected interface(if loopback_... parameters are specified).
At the end the number of BFD router interfaces per BFD router will be: intf_count * loopback_count * gre_count.
Each BFD router interface will be associated to:

  • a directly connected interface, if the user specifies only the intf_... parameters
  • an unconnected/loopback interface, if the user specifies the intf_... and the loopback_... parameters
  • a GRE tunnel, if the user specifies:
    • the intf_... and the loopback_... and gre_... parameters
    • the intf_ and the gre_... parameters

echo_rx_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

This is the minimum interval, in microseconds, between received BFD Echo packets that this system is capable of supporting. If this value is zero, the transmitting system does not support the receipt of BFD Echo packets. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

echo_timeout

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The value must be chosen in such a way so that the session liveliness should be verified by Echo conveniently. Remember, since Echo Time Out is configurable, it is possible that the session may have a higher Echo Time Out than BFD Control Time Out. On expiry of Echo Time Out the session will be deleted and the entire process of BFD session establishment will happen from the DOWN state. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -echo_tx_interval is present and has a value greater than or equal to 50 and -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

1500

echo_tx_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

If Echo Tx interval is configured, Echo packets will be sent at an interval of Echo Tx interval. If the configurable Echo Tx interval is not set to a value greater than 50, the transmitter will use the Echo Rx interval of the connected device to send its Echo Packets. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

enable_ctrl_plane_independent

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

If set, the transmitting system's BFD implementation does not share fate with its control plane (in other words, BFD is implemented in the forwarding plane and can continue to function through disruptions in the control plane). If clear, the transmitting system's BFD implementation shares fate with its control plane. The use of this bit is application dependent and is outside the scope of this specification. This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

enable_demand_mode

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

BFD has two operating modes which may be selected, as well as an additional function that can be used in combination with the two modes, the echo function. This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

Valid options are:

0

Asynchronous mode. In this mode, the systems periodically send BFD Control packets to one another, and if a number of those packets in a row are not received by the other system, the session is declared to be down. If -enable_demand_mode is set to 0, the system will be in asynchronous mode.

1

Demand mode. In this mode, once a BFD session is established, the systems stop sending BFD Control packets, except when either system feels the need to verify connectivity explicitly, in which case a short sequence of BFD Control packets is sent, and then the protocol again stops sending Control packets. If enable_demand_mode is set to 1, the system will be in demand mode.

DEFAULT

0

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

BFD sessions will flap every flap_tx_interval (ms).This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

If the loopback_... parameters are present the GRE interface will be connected through the loopback interface, otherwise it will be connected through the directly connected interface.This option is valid only when -mode is create and -gre_ip_addr and/or -gre_ipv6_addr are present.

gre_ip_addr_lstep

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The IPv4 address incrementing step of the GRE tunnels that will be configured when passing from one loopback interface to another.
This option is valid only when -mode is create and -gre_ip_addr is present.
When gre_src_ip_addr_mode is routed, then both gre_ip_addr_cstep and gre_ip_addr_lstep must be present if this kind of incrementing is wanted. If only one of them is present, the two parameters are ignored and only gre_ip_addr_step is taken into account.
When gre_src_ip_addr_mode is connected, then only gre_ip_addr_cstep will be considered. If gre_ip_addr_cstep is not present, the incrementing is based on gre_ip_addr_step.
Example:

  1. The GRE tunnels have the loopback interfaces as source.
    intf_count 2
    loopback_count 2
    gre_count 3
    gre_src_ip_addr_mode routed
    gre_ip_addr 1.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_step 0.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_lstep 0.0.1.0
    gre_ip_addr_cstep 0.1.0.0
    The following list of GRE IP addresses will be generated:
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE1 - 1.0.0.1;
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE2 - 1.0.0.2;
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE3 - 1.0.0.3;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE4 - 1.0.1.1;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE5 - 1.0.1.2;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE6 - 1.0.1.3;

    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE7 - 1.1.0.1;
    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE8 - 1.1.0.2;
    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE9 - 1.1.0.3;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE10 - 1.1.1.1;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE11 - 1.1.1.2;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE12 - 1.1.1.3;
  2. The GRE tunnels have the connected interfaces as source
    intf_count 2
    gre_count 3
    gre_src_ip_addr_mode connected
    gre_ip_addr 1.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_step 0.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_cstep 0.1.0.0
    The following list of GRE IP addresses will be generated:
    Connected1, GRE1 - 1.0.0.1;
    Connected1, GRE2 - 1.0.0.2;
    Connected1, GRE3 - 1.0.0.3;

    Connected2, GRE7 - 1.1.0.1;
    Connected2, GRE8 - 1.1.0.2;
    Connected2, GRE9 - 1.1.0.3;

DEFAULT

 None

gre_ip_addr_cstep

Supported platforms Details

NAME - <namespace>::emulation_bfd_config

DESCRIPTION

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

This command is used to create/modify/delete/enable/disable a BFD router.
Each BFD router can have multiple BFD router interfaces.
Each router interface is associated with a protocol interface.
By specifying the intf_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to intf_count of directly connected interfaces per BFD router.
By specifying the loopback_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to loopback_count of unconnected interfaces per connected interface.
By specifying the gre_... parameters there will be created a number of interfaces equal to gre_count of unconnected interfaces per connected interface(if no loopback_... parameters are specified) or per unconnected interface(if loopback_... parameters are specified).
At the end the number of BFD router interfaces per BFD router will be: intf_count * loopback_count * gre_count.
Each BFD router interface will be associated to:

  • a directly connected interface, if the user specifies only the intf_... parameters
  • an unconnected/loopback interface, if the user specifies the intf_... and the loopback_... parameters
  • a GRE tunnel, if the user specifies:
    • the intf_... and the loopback_... and gre_... parameters
    • the intf_ and the gre_... parameters

echo_rx_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

This is the minimum interval, in microseconds, between received BFD Echo packets that this system is capable of supporting. If this value is zero, the transmitting system does not support the receipt of BFD Echo packets. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

echo_timeout

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The value must be chosen in such a way so that the session liveliness should be verified by Echo conveniently. Remember, since Echo Time Out is configurable, it is possible that the session may have a higher Echo Time Out than BFD Control Time Out. On expiry of Echo Time Out the session will be deleted and the entire process of BFD session establishment will happen from the DOWN state. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -echo_tx_interval is present and has a value greater than or equal to 50 and -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

1500

echo_tx_interval

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

If Echo Tx interval is configured, Echo packets will be sent at an interval of Echo Tx interval. If the configurable Echo Tx interval is not set to a value greater than 50, the transmitter will use the Echo Rx interval of the connected device to send its Echo Packets. The supported range is 0-4,294,967,295, and the enable range is 50-4,294,967,295. All values between 1-49 will be considered as the minimum timer of 50.When the Echo function is active, a stream of BFD Echo packets is transmitted in such a way as to have the other system loop them back through its forwarding path( same source and destination IP in the Echo packet sent on a specific UDP Port No ). If a number of packets of the echoed data stream are not received, the session is declared to be down.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

enable_ctrl_plane_independent

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

If set, the transmitting system's BFD implementation does not share fate with its control plane (in other words, BFD is implemented in the forwarding plane and can continue to function through disruptions in the control plane). If clear, the transmitting system's BFD implementation shares fate with its control plane. The use of this bit is application dependent and is outside the scope of this specification. This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

DEFAULT

0

enable_demand_mode

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

BFD has two operating modes which may be selected, as well as an additional function that can be used in combination with the two modes, the echo function. This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is provided.

Valid options are:

0

Asynchronous mode. In this mode, the systems periodically send BFD Control packets to one another, and if a number of those packets in a row are not received by the other system, the session is declared to be down. If -enable_demand_mode is set to 0, the system will be in asynchronous mode.

1

Demand mode. In this mode, once a BFD session is established, the systems stop sending BFD Control packets, except when either system feels the need to verify connectivity explicitly, in which case a short sequence of BFD Control packets is sent, and then the protocol again stops sending Control packets. If enable_demand_mode is set to 1, the system will be in demand mode.

DEFAULT

0

gre_ip_addr_lstep

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The IPv4 address incrementing step of the GRE tunnels that will be configured when passing from one loopback interface to another.
This option is valid only when -mode is create and -gre_ip_addr is present.
When gre_src_ip_addr_mode is routed, then both gre_ip_addr_cstep and gre_ip_addr_lstep must be present if this kind of incrementing is wanted. If only one of them is present, the two parameters are ignored and only gre_ip_addr_step is taken into account.
When gre_src_ip_addr_mode is connected, then only gre_ip_addr_cstep will be considered. If gre_ip_addr_cstep is not present, the incrementing is based on gre_ip_addr_step.
Example:

  1. The GRE tunnels have the loopback interfaces as source.
    intf_count 2
    loopback_count 2
    gre_count 3
    gre_src_ip_addr_mode routed
    gre_ip_addr 1.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_step 0.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_lstep 0.0.1.0
    gre_ip_addr_cstep 0.1.0.0
    The following list of GRE IP addresses will be generated:
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE1 - 1.0.0.1;
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE2 - 1.0.0.2;
    Connected1, Loopback1,GRE3 - 1.0.0.3;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE4 - 1.0.1.1;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE5 - 1.0.1.2;
    Connected1, Loopback2,GRE6 - 1.0.1.3;

    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE7 - 1.1.0.1;
    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE8 - 1.1.0.2;
    Connected2, Loopback1,GRE9 - 1.1.0.3;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE10 - 1.1.1.1;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE11 - 1.1.1.2;
    Connected2, Loopback2,GRE12 - 1.1.1.3;
  2. The GRE tunnels have the connected interfaces as source
    intf_count 2
    gre_count 3
    gre_src_ip_addr_mode connected
    gre_ip_addr 1.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_step 0.0.0.1
    gre_ip_addr_cstep 0.1.0.0
    The following list of GRE IP addresses will be generated:
    Connected1, GRE1 - 1.0.0.1;
    Connected1, GRE2 - 1.0.0.2;
    Connected1, GRE3 - 1.0.0.3;

    Connected2, GRE7 - 1.1.0.1;
    Connected2, GRE8 - 1.1.0.2;
    Connected2, GRE9 - 1.1.0.3;

DEFAULT

 None

The incrementing step for VPI when creating directly connected protocol interfaces.This option is valid only when -mode is create or -mode is modify and -handle is a BFD router interface.When vpi_step causes the vpi value to exceed its maximum value the increment will be done modulo .Examples: vpi = 254; vpi_step = 2 -> new vpi value = 0vpi = 255; vpi_step = 11 -> new vpi value = 10

DEFAULT

 None

vci_step

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The incrementing step for VCI when creating directly connected protocol interfaces. When vci_step causes the vci value to exceed its maximum value the increment will be done modulo <number of possible vci ids>.
Examples:

  • vci = 65534; vci_step = 2 -> new vci value = 0
  • vci = 65535; vci_step = 11 -> new vci value = 10

DEFAULT

 None

RETURN VALUES

Supported Platform Details

All

log

On status of failure, gives detailed information.

router_interface_handles.

interface_handles.

On mode create, list of protocol interface handles for a specific <router_handle>
